# Memory Management Strategy & Guideline
*Derived from OpenClaw memory-core + memory-lancedb codebase analysis*
*Date: 2026-03-03*

---

## 1. Overview

This document extracts the design patterns, architectural decisions, and operational guidelines from the OpenClaw memory system so they can be reused in other AI agent projects. The system solves a hard problem: giving an AI agent durable, searchable memory across sessions without sacrificing explainability, security, or offline capability.

---

## 2. The Five-Database Architecture

The codebase uses five distinct storage roles, each optimized for a different access pattern. Understanding why each exists is the first step to replicating or adapting the design.

### 2.1 Database Role Map

| # | Store | Technology | Purpose | Search type |
|---|-------|-----------|---------|------------|
| 1 | Canonical (source of truth) | Markdown files (git-tracked) | Human-readable, append-only daily logs + curated long-term facts | N/A — the authoritative record |
| 2 | Vector index | LanceDB (or SQLite `vec0`) | Semantic / fuzzy recall | Cosine / L2 distance |
| 3 | Full-text index | SQLite FTS5 | Exact-token / keyword recall | BM25 ranking |
| 4 | Embedding cache | SQLite (kv table) | Avoid re-embedding unchanged chunks | Exact key lookup |
| 5 | Hybrid sidecar (optional) | QMD (BM25 + vector + reranker) | All-in-one local retrieval with reranking | BM25 + vector + learned rerank |

**Principle:** The Markdown files are always the truth. Every other store is a *derived index* that can be deleted and rebuilt from Markdown at any time.

