## 3. Input Processing Pipeline

### 3.1 Capture Decision (Auto-Capture Filter)

Not every user message deserves to be stored. The codebase applies a four-gate filter before writing anything:

```
Input text
    │
    ├── Gate 1: Length check (10 ≤ chars ≤ captureMaxChars, default 500)
    │           → reject if too short (noise) or too long (bulk dump)
    │
    ├── Gate 2: Content smell check
    │           → reject if already injected memory context (<relevant-memories>)
    │           → reject if looks like system/XML content (<tag>...</tag>)
    │           → reject if agent output (markdown bold + bullet list pattern)
    │           → reject if emoji-heavy (> 3 emoji = agent-generated, not user)
    │
    ├── Gate 3: Prompt-injection screen
    │           → reject if matches PROMPT_INJECTION_PATTERNS regex set
    │           → patterns include: "ignore previous instructions", "system prompt",
    │             "<system>", "execute tool", etc.
    │
    └── Gate 4: Memory-trigger check
                → only capture if text matches at least one MEMORY_TRIGGER pattern
                → triggers: preference phrases, personal facts, explicit "remember",
                  contact info (email / phone), decision phrases
```

**Implementation guideline for new projects:**
- Always process *only user-role messages*, never assistant/model output (prevents self-poisoning).
- Keep the trigger list narrow and explicit; false positives pollute the memory store.
- Cap `captureMaxChars` at 500 by default; let users raise it deliberately.
- Limit auto-capture to 3 items per conversation turn to bound growth.

### 3.2 Category Detection

After deciding to capture, classify the text into one of five categories:

| Category | Detection heuristic | Example |
|----------|-------------------|---------|
| `preference` | "prefer", "like", "love", "hate", "want" | "I prefer dark mode" |
| `decision` | "decided", "will use", "budeme" | "We decided to use React" |
| `entity` | phone/email regex, "is called", "jmenuje se" | "My email is a@b.com" |
| `fact` | "is", "are", "has", "have" | "The server runs on port 3000" |
| `other` | fallback | Anything unclassified |

**Guideline:** Categories drive retrieval filtering and surfacing logic downstream. Expand them for your domain (e.g., add `action_item`, `code_snippet`, `deadline`).

### 3.3 Embedding Generation

Once capture is approved, generate a vector embedding before writing:

```
text → embedding model (e.g. text-embedding-3-small, 1536 dims)
     → near-duplicate check: search existing vectors at threshold ≥ 0.95
     → if duplicate found: skip storage, return existing entry reference
     → if no duplicate: store {id, text, vector, category, importance, createdAt}
```

**Near-duplicate threshold guidance:**
- `≥ 0.95` for storage (high bar prevents redundant writes)
- `≥ 0.7` for forget-by-query (moderate confidence before deletion)
- `≥ 0.3` for auto-recall injection (broad recall into context)
- `≥ 0.1` for explicit `memory_recall` tool call (widest net for user queries)

